{"summary":"All three amendments are technically justified. The first improves observability around a potentially lossy legacy-repair fallback, and the other two address real task-run lineage correctness defects: ambiguous mixed-open reuse and silent `plan_hash` conflict masking.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-11-9348c590","decision":"accept","rationale":"The fallback at `fs.rs:2449-2453` performs a lossy overwrite of malformed legacy details with no signal. Adding a warning there is low-risk and materially improves auditability for a path that may discard conflicting data. It is not a full semantic fix, but it is still a sound safety/maintainability improvement."},{"amendment_id":"fr-11-3f2dfcd6","decision":"accept","rationale":"This is a real correctness bug. `record_task_run_start` can reuse a single runless open row even when another named open attempt for the same bead/project already exists, which leaves multiple concurrent open attempts and corrupts lineage attribution. Rejecting that mixed-open state is safer and consistent with `update_task_run` treating ambiguous open matches as corruption."},{"amendment_id":"fr-11-84b6b1d6","decision":"accept","rationale":"This is a lineage-integrity defect. In the open-to-terminal update path, a conflicting `plan_hash` is silently ignored once the running row already has a value, so the call reports success while persisting stale metadata. For audit fields, silently dropping conflicting caller input is incorrect; the code should either reject the mismatch or explicitly overwrite it."}]}